quote:The ethical issue here is not whether or not to allow "citizens [to] throw their money away", but rather whether others should knowingly take it. Just because someone is willing to part with money due to ignorance or addiction doesn't mean that it's ethical for another to accept it with awareness of the the one's ignorance or addiction. Total straw man. I'm tired of people clamoring for laws because of some ethical obligation, and usually one for which the ethical quandary is most certainly not set in stone (it's alright to gamble in Vegas or some Seminole Indian casino in South Florida, but not on-line?). This would be a sad country indeed were every activity, product, and service that could be deemed addictive were banned due to "ethical" concerns.Part of living in a free society is accepting that you have both the freedom to succeed and to fail. Take away one of those options and you no longer have a free society. Personally I'd prefer legit organizations along with the government via taxes keep taking in the money instead of areas with no gambling concession being owned entirely by the mob, gangs, and other undesirables.
