Posted: Fri Mar 27, 2009 11:41 am
Ethics? Why are people talking about ethics? The ban on online gambling has absolutely nothing to do with ethics.It does have everything to do with Harrah's/MGM/etc lobbying for its prevention. Take for example the Lake Tahoe casinos. They've seen a dramatic decline in customer visits over the last decade or so. The sole reason for this is that a number of Native America casinos have opened up in the Western Sierra foothills and now residents of Sacramento and the Bay Area don't have to drive as far to get their gambling fix. Likewise, with the rise in Native American casinos across the country; people don't feel the need to visit Vegas or Atlantic City as much anymore.Tahoe has been able to make up for it by flying top customers in and trading free stays for gaming revenue.Vegas makes up for it by offering world class shopping and dining in addition to the sin. Other than that, people simply don't feel the need to spend a bunch of money on an expensive flight and trip when they can just go to the local Native American joint and get their fix.Now imagine you can gamble from the comfort of your own home. The big gaming companies don't want that, the Native American casinos don't want that, race tracks don't want that...Dear Senator...
nightwing2000
Ars Centurion
Registered: May 4, 2007Posts: 248
Posted: Fri Mar 27, 2009 11:50 am
Anyone who's bored and wants to see US arrogance in the face of trade committments, might want to look up the USA-Canada softwood lumber trade dispute. The US, on the urging of some lobbyists in western states, has claimed that the low stumpage rates charged by the Canadian provinces for crown lands was somehow an unfair subsidy. Despite provisions in the NAFTA (Free Trade Agreement) and the WTO; despite losing almost every case brought against it; despite the blatant illegality of its actions - the country persisted in collecting billions in tariffs; as each alw was struck down in court, a new one replaced it. The weenies in Canada's government under Stephen Harper finally caved in and agreed to collect their own tariff and limit quantities if the US returned a fraction of theillegal tariffs already collected. We're not talking a major product like Hollywood, or banking, or oil - this is frickin' woodies, like 2x4's and plywood. Pretty pathetic, eh?So don't expect anything different from gambling. A few influential lobbyists with the right ears can work wonders in congress. "The force can have a strong influence on the weak-minded".
